Relationships between variables:

We will start with the per capita crime rate (crime) as it is the parameter we will be observing in this exercise

  1. The crime rate shows a highy positive correlation with

  • higher proportion of non-retail businesses (indus),

  • nitrous oxide levels (nox),

  • accessibility to radial highways (rad), and

  • property tax rates (tax)

  1. Crime rate is negatively correlated with:

  • Distance to the employment centres (dis)

  • Proportion of the black population (black) (Racists will say this is fake)

  • value of owner-occupied homes (medv)

  1. The most strongly correlated variables:

  • proportion of non-retail businesses and distance to the employment centres: negative correlation

  • proportion of non-retail businesses and nitrous oxide levels: positive correlation (makes sense- industrialization and not very healthy emissions go hand in hand)

  • proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940 (age) and distance to the employment centres: negative correlation (It appears the employment centres were built away from residential areas)

We can see that integers have been converted to decimal values now. Hence we now have a dataset with all continuous variables, with both positive and negative values.The variables in the new dataset have been standardized so thet the mean value for each variable is 0.

Now, we will start to look at the relationships of the per capita crime rate with other variables.

Converting the new scaled crime rate (crim) to factor with the quantiles as intervals. We will label this variable “crime”:

boston_scaled$crim <- as.numeric(boston_scaled$crim)

bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)


boston_scaled$crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

The new variable “crime” has been divided into four levels:

  • -0.419 to -0.411 (low)

  • -0.411 to -0.39 (med_low)

  • -0.39 to 0.00739 (med_high)

  • 0.00739 to 9.92 (high)

Clustering and analysis:

Creating the train and test datasets to check the performance of our models:

nrow(Boston)
## [1] 506
# to keep 80% (0.8) of the rows in the train dataset, we need to multiply the total number of rows in the complete dataset by 0.8

n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

test$correct_classes <- test$crime

test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

dim(train)
## [1] 404  14
dim(test)

It appears a few observations have been placed in the wrong classes, but this error only exists for the low-medium classes.Only one observation from the high crime rate has been predicted to fall in the med_high class. The highest errors exist for observations of the class “low”, which have been predicted to fall in one class above. The rest seem acceptable.

This one has the lowest within-cluster variability so far, making it the better of the three models we have just tried.

Let’s try another method to determine the optimal number of clusters:

set.seed(123)
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss})

qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')
## Warning: `qplot()` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(Boston, centers = k_max)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

It does appear that the within-cluster variability changes considerably when we change the number of clusters from 1 to 2 and 3. However, the lowest value is obtained at around 8-9.

Bonus exercises:

clusters <- as.numeric(km3$cluster)
boston_scaled$clusters <- clusters
lda2 <- lda(clusters ~ ., data = boston_scaled)
lda2.pred <- predict(lda2, newdata = boston_scaled)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  graphics::arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}


# plot the lda results (select both lines and execute them at the same time!)
plot(lda2, dimen = 3)
lda.arrows(lda2, myscale = 5)

So we can see that some of the factors with the greatest influence on theis clustering are age, tax, nox and crime rates.
